	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Academic assessment of EU–South Africa TDCA published</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>As part of its annual publication ‘Monitoring regional integration in Southern Africa’, the Trade Law Centre for Southern Africa has posted an article assessing the impact of the EU–South Africa TDCA. It seeks to assess ‘how effective the TDCA has been in promoting South African agricultural exports’. It argues that:</p>
<ul>

<li>37.2% of South Africa’s agricultural exports are ‘real star’ performers, in that ‘South Africa is gaining market share in a strongly growing EU market’;</li>

<li>19.2% of trade is in tariff lines which are seen as ‘star’ performers, in that ‘South Africa is doing very well in a growth EU market’;</li>

<li>Only 1% of trade is in tariff lines where South African exporters are fighting a ‘forlorn battle and losing on all fronts’.</li>

</ul>
<p>Overall it is considered that ‘just over three quarters of (agricultural) exports are performing well’. However, according to this analysis, ‘[the level of] exports to the EU as a percentage of South African total agricultural exports is declining’.</p><p>In terms of the impact of the TDCA, the picture is mixed. Overall, average EU tariffs on agricultural imports from South Africa have not been subject to significant general reduction in tariffs, as the average duty paid in 2009 was 6.4%, compared to 7.1% prevailing under the pre-TDCA tariffs. However detailed data reveal wide variations in the tariff changes: the savings in duties that have resulted from the implementation of TDCA tariff reduction commitments are concentrated in wine and horticultural products, which have enjoyed a particularly strong export performance.</p><a name="eztoc470116_0_0_0_0_1" id="eztoc470116_0_0_0_0_1"></a><h6>Changes in EU duties on ‘star’ performing South African exports</h6><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
