<p>Source: extracted from Table 5, p. 93 of the source cited below</p><p>In terms of EU food and agricultural exports to South Africa, the EU’s market share of total exports initially declined (from between 30% and 33% of total agricultural imports in the 1998–2006 period to a low of 20.1% in 2004) but subsequently recovered somewhat to a 27.3% share in 2009, a level more or less comparable to the share in 2000 (27.5%). This is despite the fact that the level of tariff reductions on EU exports to South Africa is far greater than the level of tariff reductions on South African exports to the EU (average tariffs applied on agricultural exports from the EU to South Africa fell from 12.2% to 6.5%).</p><p>However this is merely a ‘snapshot’ of the agricultural trade position, with a wide range of factors beyond the TDCA influencing both the total level of food and agricultural imports and the source of these imports (including exchange rate movements).</p><p>Overall the TRALAC analysis argued that ‘the EU is doing well but … the impacts of the tariff reductions are more muted than the comparable reductions for South African agricultural imports into the EU’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>TRALAC/the Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung, ‘An assessment of the Trade, Development and Cooperation Agreement (TDCA)’ by R. Sandrey, Chapter 5 of <i>Monitoring regional integration in southern Africa: Yearbook 2010</i>, 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.givengain.com/cause_data/images/1694/FINAL_MRI_book_20110706cover.pdf" target="_self">http://www.givengain.com/cause_data/images/1694/FINAL_MRI_book_20110706c...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>While the EU continues to maintain relatively high average tariffs on agricultural imports from South Africa, at the detailed level there appears to be a closer correlation between tariff reductions and export performance. This highlights why the South African government is attaching so much importance to securing further tariff reductions for its agricultural exports as part of the SADC–EU EPA negotiations.</p><p>In the late 1990s when the TDCA was being negotiated, the process of CAP reform was still in its early stages. Since then, several major rounds of CAP reform have been agreed and implemented, effectively preparing a growing range of EU agricultural sectors for more liberalised trade. This has provided the basis for the granting of a range of new tariff preferences to both developing countries and developed economies.</p><p>The prospect of South Africa securing expanded tariff preferences for agricultural exports exacerbates the concerns of neighbouring SADC EPA configuration governments as regards the accelerating process of preference erosion faced on the EU market. In this context, there would appear to be a need to increasingly pay attention to the many non-tariff issues which represent either potential new non-tariff barriers to trade, or increase the costs of exporting to the EU market.</p><p>An illustrative example in this respect would be establishing a dialogue with SADC beef exporters on how new EU production standards (e.g. animal welfare-related requirements) can be applied in a manner consistent with local realities (e.g. not requiring fully enclosed cattle trucks in high-temperature zones, so as to avoid causing undue heat distress to cattle during transportation), while respecting the underlying objectives of these EU production standards. A further example would be the initiation of ‘aid for trade’ support to assist in the repositioning of SADC export products on EU markets in response to the accelerating process of preference erosion.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
